==English==

===Etymology===
From {{bor|en|la|hilaris||cheerful}}, from {{der|en|grc|ἱλαρός||cheerful, merry}}, from {{m|grc|ἵλαος||propitious, gracious, kind}}.

===Pronunciation===
*{{a|UK}} {{IPA|/hɪˈlɛəriəs/|lang=en}}
*{{a|US}} {{IPA|1=/hɪˈleriəs/|2=/haɪˈleriəs/|lang=en}}
*{{rhymes|ɛəriəs|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# Very [[funny]]; causing great [[merriment]] and [[laughter]].
# Full of hilarity; merry.
#* {{quote-text|year=1944|author=Douglas Stewart|title=A Girl with Red Hair, and Other Stories|page=60|passage=Rounding up the animals in the misty paddocks, with the blackbirds singing as the morning whitened, he felt '''hilarious''', light-headed. He'd clap the cows on their rumps and shout "Come along, there! Come along there, me Irish darlint."}}

